  "text": "Django QuerySets implement lazy evaluation through a multi-layer architecture. When a QuerySet is first iterated, an OperationalError is raised at the point where the underlying database query is executed.\n\nThe lazy evaluation mechanism is implemented in django/db/models/query.py. The QuerySet class initializes with _result_cache = None in __init__ (lines 306-321), which tracks whether the QuerySet has been evaluated. When iteration begins via __iter__ (lines 407-412), it immediately calls _fetch_all() (lines 2093-2097). The _fetch_all() method checks if _result_cache is None, and if so, instantiates the _iterable_class (typically ModelIterable) and converts it to a list, which triggers the actual database query.\n\nThe ModelIterable class (lines 88-164) implements the iterable that performs the actual query execution. Its __iter__ method (lines 91-163) calls compiler.execute_sql() at line 98, passing control to the SQL compilation layer.\n\nThe SQL compilation and execution occurs in django/db/models/sql/compiler.py. The SQLCompiler.execute_sql() method (lines 1601-1673) first compiles the SQL via as_sql() at line 1618, then executes the query via cursor.execute() at line 1631. This is where the database connection is accessed and the OperationalError would be raised if the connection is invalid or unavailable. The SQLCompiler.results_iter() method (lines 1571-1592) also participates in the execution chain by calling execute_sql() at line 1580 if results are not already provided.\n\nThe database cursor execution is handled in django/db/backends/utils.py. The CursorWrapper.execute() method (lines 100-105) wraps the native database cursor and calls either self.cursor.execute(sql) or self.cursor.execute(sql, params) at lines 103 or 105, depending on whether parameters are provided. This is the final point where the database driver receives the query for execution.\n\nThe complete execution chain when a QuerySet is first iterated is: QuerySet.__iter__() → QuerySet._fetch_all() → ModelIterable.__iter__() → SQLCompiler.execute_sql() → cursor.execute(). An OperationalError would be raised at the cursor.execute() call if there are database connection issues."
}

